Advance CSS Selectors : ---------

1️⃣ Descendant selector
              .descendant p{
                  color: blue;
                  font-style: italic;
              }
Meaning
Select all <p> elements that are inside an element with class descendant (at any depth).

Example HTML
              <div class="descendant">
                  <p>Paragraph 1</p>
                  <div>
                      <p>Paragraph 2</p>
                  </div>
              </div>
Both paragraphs will be styled.

Result
        Paragraph 1 → blue italic
        Paragraph 2 → blue italic

Because the rule means:                 
                    .descendant
                       ↓
                    any p inside


2️⃣ Child selector
                .child > p{
                    color: red;
                    font-weight: bold;
                }
Meaning
Select only <p> elements that are direct children of .child.

Example HTML
                <div class="child">
                    <p>Direct child</p>
                
                    <div>
                        <p>Nested paragraph</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
Result
          Direct child → red bold
          Nested paragraph → NOT styled
Because > selects only direct children.



3️⃣ Attribute selector
                  input[type="text"]{
                      border: 2px solid green;
                      padding: 5px;
                  }
Meaning
        Select <input> elements where:
            type = text
            Example HTML
            <input type="text">
            <input type="password">
Result
        text input → styled
        password input → not styled



4️⃣ Data attribute selector
                  button[data-type="special"]{
                      background-color: yellow;
                      font-size: 18px;
                  }
Meaning
        Select buttons with a custom attribute.

Example HTML:
              <button data-type="special">Click</button>
              <button>Normal</button>
Result
              special button → yellow background
              normal button → unchanged

Custom attributes usually start with:
data-

Example:
          data-user
          data-role
          data-type



Other important CSS selectors
5️⃣ Universal selector
                  *{
                      margin: 0;
                      padding: 0;
                  }
Selects every element on the page.
Often used for CSS resets.

6️⃣ Group selector
              h1, h2, h3{
                  color: blue;
              }
Applies the same style to multiple elements.

7️⃣ Adjacent sibling selector
              h2 + p{
                  color: green;
              }
Selects the first paragraph immediately after an h2.
Example:
              <h2>Title</h2>
              <p>Styled</p>
              <p>Not styled</p>

8️⃣ General sibling selector
              h2 ~ p{
                  color: purple;
              }
Selects all paragraphs after h2.

Example:
              <h2>Title</h2>
              <p>Styled</p>
              <p>Styled</p>

9️⃣ Pseudo-class selectors
These style elements in specific states.

1.Hover
          button:hover{
              background: blue;
          }
When the mouse is over the button.

2.Focus
            input:focus{
                border: 2px solid blue;
            }
When input is selected.

3.First child
            li:first-child{
                font-weight: bold;
            }
Targets the first item in a list.

3.Last child
            li:last-child{
                color: red;
            }
Targets the last item.


🔟 Pseudo-elements
These style parts of elements.

1.First letter
            p::first-letter{
                font-size: 30px;
            }

2.Before
            h2::before{
                content: "⭐ ";
            }
Adds content before the element.

3.After
          h2::after{
              content: " ✔";
          }
Adds content after the element.

